full_title: Fresh Out The Slammer by Taylor Swift
title: Fresh Out The Slammer

description.plain:
“Fresh Out The Slammer”, slammer meaning jail, makes it look like Swift is talking about her relationship as if it were a prison, and that she’s finally escaped. The lyrics,

Gray and blue and fights and tunnels, Handcuffed to the spell I was under,
For just one hour of sunshine,
Years of labor, locks, and ceilings
In the shade of how he was feeling,
But it’s gonna be alright, I did my time.

and,

Now, pretty baby, I’m runnin' back home to you
Fresh out the slammer, I know who my first call will be to

support the apposed theory of their relationship being a prison (or slammer).

As well as centering around the theory mentioned above, the song also sings about knowing who she wants to rebound with after escaping the jail of her old relationship.
It starts to finally be put together when you look at Swift’s Bejeweled on her 10th studio album, Midnights. The lyric, “Don’t put me in the basement when I want the penthouse of your heart,” hints that Joe Alwyn was restricting Swift from being herself.

In the epilogue for THE TORTURED POETS DEPARTMENT, Swift also mentions her former relationship with actor Joe Alwyn as being a slammer, and her brief fling with Matty Healy as a ‘tidal wave’ that also fell apart.

“Out of the slammer and into a tidal wave / How gallant to save the empress from her gilded tower / Swinging a sword he could barely lift.
But loneliness struck at that fateful hour / Low hanging fruit on his wine stained lips / He never even scratched the surface of me / None of them did.”

I will never lose my baby again
